\begin_body

\begin_layout Section
Automatic sentiment indexes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We analyse articles of the economics section of the weekly newspaper 
\shape italic
The New York Times
\shape default
 obtained using 
\begin_inset Formula $LexisNexis$
\end_inset

, a research tool, that have been published between 1990:06 and 2013:08
 from its publically available online archive.
 We extract the sentiment of news articles using a lexicon based algorithm
 provided by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "rinker"

\end_inset

) in the open Software project R (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "rlanguage"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each article is attributed a sentiment value, 
\begin_inset Formula $ArticleValue$
\end_inset

, defined as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
ArticleValue=\frac{\Sigma_{j}^{N}wordvalue_{j}\times n_{j}}{N},
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $wordvalue_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the sentiment value attributed to word 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,...,N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the number of words of the respective article.
 The value is based on the lexicon provided by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "hu2004mining"

\end_inset

, a publicly available English-language resource for sentiment analysis.
 It contains positive and negative sentiment bearing words.
 The version employed here (SentiWS v1.8b) contains 4776 negative and 2003
 positive words.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The articles are evaluated sentence by sentence.
 Each positive word is counted as 1 and each negative word as -1.
 Then, the value found in the lexicon is refined in the following way.
 If negators like 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $not$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are found in the proximity (4 words before and 2 words after the word)
 and if the number of negators is odd the polarity of a word is inverted.
 Furthermore, if there are amplifiers like 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $very$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or de-amplifiers 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $little$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are in the proximity, the value is increased respectively decreased.
 For a detailed description of the implentation see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "rinker"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset bibtex
LatexCommand bibtex
bibfiles "MTI,mti_ip"
options "plainnat"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_body
